{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "The benefits of generating media attention may be skewing research studies and broadening their findings.", "abstract": "Revelation of misrepresented data in Michael LaCour study about gay-marriage advocacy highlights growing concern that social scientists may be subtly or unintentionally skewing results and broadening findings in order to court media attention; researchers describe tremendous pressure to produce results for academic publications that ignite larger public interest; secondary problem is that many journalists are unable to distinguish good research from bad, allowing flawed results to spread quickly.", "section_name": "Business Day", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Noam", "role": "reported", "lastname": "SCHEIBER", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By NOAM SCHEIBER"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/01/business/beyond-publish-or-perish-scientific-papers-look-to-make-splash.html", "lead_paragraph": "The benefits of generating media attention may be skewing research studies and broadening their findings.", "headline": {"main": "Academics Seek a Big Splash", "print_headline": "Beyond Publish or Perish, Academic Papers Look to Make Splash "}, "_id": "556bba1538f0d80ad152c8db", "word_count": "1467", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/06/01/business/01study-jp-1/01study-jp-1-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/06/01/business/01study-jp-1/01study-jp-1-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 764, "url": "images/2015/06/01/business/01study-jp-1/01study-jp-1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/06/01/business/01study-jp-1/01study-jp-1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "764"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/06/01/business/01study-jp-1/01study-